                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d852">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/6577: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Palmer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-08T18:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 8, 1940—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 9—5:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>127. Confidentially informed by unimpeachable source that Turkey has threatened
                    to seize two stretches of Baghdad Railway in Syria unless it is allowed the
                    right to transit war material from Basra to Turkey. Orders from Armistice
                    Commission through Vichy have been received to forbid such use of railway.
                    Turkey has right to transit war material under railway agreement which forms
                    part of Treaty of Friendship and Good Neighborship recently concluded but which
                    has not been put into effect as Turkey requested, delay in so doing on the
                    ground that the situation was too unstable. Local authorities are searching for
                    a practical solution satisfactory to Turks as they are convinced that if Turkey
                    executes its threat Iraq will take portion of Jezireh, Druzes will rebel and
                    English may move forward from Palestine. Same source states that British war
                    material is reaching Alexandretta but that port facilities are too limited.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Vichy, Ankara, Baghdad and Jerusalem.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Palmer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
